## CART using rpart()
#Building model on Training Data
News.rpart <- rpart(shares ~ ., method = "class", data = News.train)
News.rpart <- rpart(shares ~ n_tokens_title + n_tokens_content + 
                      n_unique_tokens + n_non_stop_words + 
                      num_hrefs + num_self_hrefs + 
                      num_imgs + average_token_length + 
                      num_keywords + news_channel + kw_min_min + 
                      kw_max_min + kw_avg_min + 
                      kw_min_max + kw_min_avg + 
                      kw_max_avg + kw_avg_avg + 
                      self_reference_min_shares + self_reference_max_shares + 
                      day_published + 
                      LDA_02 + global_subjectivity + 
                      global_rate_positive_words + min_positive_polarity + 
                      avg_negative_polarity + abs_title_subjectivity + 
                      abs_title_sentiment_polarity, method = "class", data = News.train)

rpart.plot(News.rpart,type=1,extra=105, main = "Classification (RPART). Classification Tree for News", faclen=0, fallen.leaves=TRUE)

printcp(News.rpart)

#KNN
#Specifies a training data set.
#2. To Predict the class of a new value, the algorthim looks for the k observations in the training set that are closest to the new value.
#3. The prediction for the new value is the class of the majority of the k nearest neighbors.


#  test for the K that gives the best classification results
pred = dim(200);
n = dim(200)


for (i in 1:15) {
  #i=1
  nearest = knn(train=News1.train, test=News1.test, cl=News1.train$shares, k=i)
  d <- data.frame(News1.test$shares,nearest)[1:1300,]
  pcorrn = sum(d[,1]==d$nearest)/1300
  pred[i] <- pcorrn
  n[i] <- i
}
pred

##  [8] 0.5453846 0.5476923 0.5561538 0.5623077 0.5592308 0.5538462 0.5476923
## [15] 0.5438462
knn.plot=data.frame(n,pred)
plot(knn.plot, ylab= "accuracy", xlab = "no. of neighbors", type ="b")
